1. WHAT CCON: IS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  CCON: is a mounted console handler - the same kind of thing CON:,
  KingCON and ViNCEd are. You mount it once, and from then on any
  program can open a console window through it, exactly as it would
  through CON:.

  The reason it exists is OUTPUT SCROLLBACK. The stock 3.2 console
  has none, and cannot be given any from the outside: commands talk
  to the handler, so a terminal program cannot bolt scrollback on.
  CCON: keeps 512 lines of history behind every window by
  default (LINESn sets it per window - up to 5000 for a deep
  transcript, or down to 100 on a tight machine).

  Around that core it grew into a full console with a modern shell
  feel:

    - every open gets its OWN window, stock CON: fashion
    - a real AmigaShell runs in it (NewShell CCON:)
    - fish-style autosuggestions from your command history
    - zsh-style tab completion with a cycling menu
    - bash-style Ctrl+R incremental history search
    - readline line surgery (Ctrl+W/U/K/L)
    - scrollback by keys and mouse wheel, in raw mode too
    - copy and paste with the stock console, both directions,
      with double-click word and triple-click line selection
    - SGR colour with a careful ANSI/Workbench pen separation,
      plus real italic/underline/inverse soft styles
    - FONT and LINES per window: your own font and scrollback
      depth, or Font Prefs' default font if you don't ask
    - fullscreen programs work: Ed with working menus, More -
      and More leaves your scrollback transcript as it found it,
      xterm-alternate-screen style
    - history is shared and persistent across every window, not
      lost when one closes
    - Ctrl+R searches scrollback CONTENT once you're scrolled
      back, not just commands - the same key, retargeted
    - RAMIGA-V pastes safely, one line at a time, never blindly
      running a whole clipboard's worth of commands
    - a raw twin device, CRAW:, for RAW:-style uses
    - can even replace CON:/RAW: system-wide, KingCON style
      (experimental - section 15)


2. REQUIREMENTS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  AmigaOS 3.2. Boot-verified on 3.2 with a 68030 (FS-UAE).
  Older OS versions are untested.

  CCON: deliberately answers the 3.2 shell's console probe in a way
  that makes the shell hand line editing to the console - that is
  where the history, completion, ghosts and search live.

  Memory: each window allocates its scrollback model at open time,
  roughly 120K at 80 columns and the default 512 lines (LINES=n
  scales it directly, up to 5000). Plenty on an expanded machine;
  mind it on a 2MB one.


3. INSTALLATION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  From the archive (the drawers mirror SYS:):

    copy L/ccon-handler L:
    copy DEVS/CCON-mountlist DEVS:
    Mount CCON: FROM DEVS:CCON-mountlist
    Mount CRAW: FROM DEVS:CCON-mountlist

  Add the two Mount lines to S:User-Startup to make them permanent.

  Try it:

    NewShell CCON:
    echo >CCON:0/0/300/80/hi/WAIT hello
    type S:Startup-sequence >CRAW:0/0/500/150/t/WAIT

  A note on updating: a running handler keeps its loaded code. After
  replacing L:ccon-handler, reboot - a re-Mount alone is not enough.


4. OPENING WINDOWS: THE NAME SYNTAX
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  The open name is stock CON: syntax. Every field may be left empty
  and options may come in any order:

    CCON:x/y/width/height/title/option/option/...

  Examples:

    NewShell CCON:
    NewShell CCON:60/30/500/120/My-Shell
    dir >CCON:0/0/400/200/dir/WAIT
    echo >CCON:0/0/300/80/log/AUTO/WAIT starting...

  A bare CCON: with no geometry opens at 0/18/640/130 - the same
  position and size a stock NewShell window opens at.

  width or height of -1 fills the REST of the screen it opens
  on, measured from X/Y - not the screen's raw size regardless of
  position, so the window's far edge always lands exactly on the
  screen's edge:

    NewShell CCON:0/0/-1/-1        (the whole screen)
    NewShell CCON:0/11/-1/-1       (everything below a title bar)
    NewShell CCON:0/0/-1/300

  EVERY open gets its own console and window, exactly as with stock
  CON:. A redirect like `list >CCON:` opens (and, without WAIT,
  closes) a window of its own. The window closes when the last
  handle on it closes.

  Opens of `*` and of CONSOLE: attach to the console the calling
  program is already running on, instead of making a new window.
  This is how a command reopens its own shell window.


5. THE OPTIONS, ONE BY ONE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  CLOSE      Put a close gadget on the window. The gadget is ON by
             default (like a 3.2 shell window). Clicking it follows
             the V47 console protocol: a shell (cooked reader) gets
             end-of-file - the click ends it, as on stock; a raw
             fullscreen program that ASKED for close-gadget reports
             gets the report and decides for itself - Ed asks, so
             the click runs Ed's own quit flow; a raw program that
             never asked gets nothing, exactly as stock gives it
             (quit More with its own keys).

  NOCLOSE    Remove the close gadget.

  WAIT       Keep the window open after the last handle closes,
             until its close gadget is clicked. Without it, output
             windows flash by:  dir >CCON:0/0//200/d/WAIT

  AUTO       The open succeeds without a window; the window only
             appears on the first actual I/O. The classic idiom for
             debug consoles that should not open until they have
             something to say.

  SCREENname Open on the named public screen, e.g. SCREENWorkbench
             or a terminal's own screen name.

  NOBORDER   No window border.
  NODRAG     No drag bar.
  NODEPTH    No depth gadget.
  NOSIZE     No sizing gadget.
  BACKDROP   A backdrop window.
  INACTIVE   Do not activate the window on open.
  PASTEEXEC  RAMIGA-V pastes the old way in this window: every LF
             in the clip runs its line immediately, no queueing.
             See section 11.

  WINDOW0xADDR
             Render into an EXISTING window at that address instead
             of opening one. This is how a terminal program hands
             its frame window to CCON:. The window is returned to
             its owner untouched on close.

  PENn       Default text pen number, 1-15. A terminal with an ANSI
             palette typically passes PEN7.

  WBPENS     Declares the screen's palette truly ANSI. Plain SGR
             30-33 from programs are then treated as WORKBENCH pen
             numbers and retargeted at the theme (C:Ed hardcodes
             WB pens; without this it would render in ANSI red).
             See section 16 for the full colour story.

  FONTname/size
             Open the window in this font, loading it from disk if
             it is not already resident. Left unset, the window
             opens in whatever font Font Prefs has set as "System
             Default Text" (topaz 8 only if that font can't be
             opened, or is proportional - proportional fonts don't
             fit the cell model). Example: FONTmicroknight/8.

  LINESn     How many lines of scrollback THIS window keeps
             (default 512, floor 100, ceiling 5000). Raise it for
             a deep transcript, lower it on a tight machine - see
             section 17 for the cost per line.
             The ring is always kept a little larger than the
             window is tall, so on a very tall window a small
             LINESn is quietly raised to fit: a window with more
             text rows than the ring holds would have nowhere to
             scroll back to.

  Not implemented: SMART, SIMPLE, ALT. (Iconify is a key - RightAmiga+I,
  section 14 - not an open option.)

  A WARNING WORTH BOLD: the AmigaDOS shell eats an unquoted '='
  from ANY command line before CCON: ever sees it - so a FONT or
  LINES option MUST be written without one (FONTtopaz/8, LINES200),
  or the whole open string quoted. `FONT=topaz/8` silently truncates
  to `FONT` and does nothing; this is a shell fact, not a CCON: bug.

  A keyword as the very FIRST field switches the whole open string
  to options-only, with default position and size - so a plain
  option needs no throwaway slashes:

    NewShell CCON:FONTtopaz/8
    NewShell CCON:WAIT
    NewShell CCON:LINES200

  Mixing geometry WITH options still needs the full positional form
  (x/y/w/h/title come first, as in section 4):

    NewShell CCON:0/0/640/200/My-Window/FONTtopaz/8


6. THE LINE EDITOR
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Cooked mode - the shell prompt - is edited by the console:

    typing            inserts at the cursor
    Left / Right      move by one character
    Ctrl+Left/Right   jump by word
    Shift+Left/Right  jump to start / end of line
    Backspace         delete before the cursor
    Del               delete under the cursor
    Shift+Backspace   delete from line start to the cursor
    Shift+Del         delete from the cursor to line end
    Esc               clear the line
    Return            commit the line
    Up / Down         walk the history (32 entries; the half-typed
                      line is stashed and comes back)
    Ctrl+W            delete the word before the cursor
    Ctrl+U            delete from line start to the cursor
                      (same as Shift+Backspace)
    Ctrl+K            delete from the cursor to line end
                      (same as Shift+Del)
    Ctrl+L            clear the screen, keeping the line - the
                      cleared rows scroll into HISTORY, so Shift+Up
                      brings them back; nothing is destroyed
    Ctrl+\            end-of-file (EndShell on an interactive shell)
    Ctrl+C..F         break signals to the running command, as on
                      any Amiga console

  Long lines wrap across rows like the stock shell: growing past
  the bottom of the window scrolls the screen, and the prompt walks
  up with it.


7. AUTOSUGGESTIONS (THE GREY GHOST)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  As you type, CCON: looks for the newest history entry that begins
  with your line (case-blind) and shows the rest of it as grey
  ghost text at the cursor:

    4.Work:> ls _-la AmigaTools/        <- "-la AmigaTools/" is
                                           grey: a suggestion

    Right / Shift+Right   accept the whole suggestion
    Ctrl+Right            accept ONE word of it (leading space
                          included: from `ls`, one stroke takes
                          ` -la`)
    anything else         just keep typing; the ghost adapts or
                          disappears

  The ghost is display only. It is never part of what Return
  commits, never copied by a selection, and it only appears at all
  on screens that have a readable grey pen - a ghost that looked
  like typed text would be worse than none.

  Tab never accepts the ghost - it always opens tab completion
  (below), ghost or no ghost. Ghosts are a Right-family thing only.


8. TAB COMPLETION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Tab completes the word at the cursor as a filename:

    - one match: completed fully; a directory gets a trailing '/',
      a file a trailing space
    - several matches: completed to the common prefix, then a MENU
      of candidates opens below the prompt

  In the menu:

    Tab          cycle forward
    Shift+Tab    cycle backwards
    Return       accept the highlighted candidate and close; the
                 line stays put, so a second Return runs it
    Esc          close the menu, line unchanged
    any other    close the menu, then act normally

  Menu colours mirror the ls scheme: directories blue, hidden-class
  entries (h-bit or .info) grey.

  Relative words complete in the current directory of the shell
  that is reading the window; words with ':' resolve through
  assigns, volumes and devices.

  Limits, by design: no quoted words, one menu page (80 candidates;
  a beep means there are more), no volume-name completion for a
  bare word.


9. CTRL+R HISTORY SEARCH
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Ctrl+R searches your history incrementally, the bash way. The
  prompt itself is replaced by an inverse banner:

    (search: fra_)  matching-command-line

  Type any fragment - it matches ANYWHERE in the line, not just at
  the start (that is the difference from the ghost). The newest
  matching history entry appears in the edit line as you type.

    Ctrl+R (again)   step to the next older match
    Backspace        shorten the fragment (search widens back)
    Return           run the shown match
    cursor keys      keep the match and edit it normally
    Esc              forget it all; your original line comes back

  A beep means no entry matches; the line keeps the last match.
  When the search ends, the real prompt returns - CCON: restores
  it from the scrollback model, pixel for pixel.

  Ctrl+R means something else once you are SCROLLED BACK - see
  "Searching scrollback" in section 10.


10. SCROLLBACK
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Every window remembers 512 lines by default (LINESn asks for
  more, up to 5000 - section 5). Viewing:

    Shift+Up / Shift+Down   page back / forward  (cooked mode)
    Ctrl+Up / Ctrl+Down     one line at a time   (ALL modes)
    mouse wheel             three lines a tick   (ALL modes)

  "All modes" means raw mode too - a raw client that just streams
  output (CRAW:, or anything that never takes the screen over) is
  scrolled back exactly like a cooked window. Ed and More are the
  exception: they run on the ALTERNATE SCREEN (section 13) for
  essentially their whole session, and scrolling is refused there,
  xterm manners - there is nothing to scroll TO until they exit and
  your transcript comes back. Raw programs never see the scroll
  keys or the wheel either way.

  While you are back, the title bar shows [scrollback -n]. Any new
  output, or any other key, snaps the view to live. Colours are
  remembered per cell and survive the trip.

  Searching scrollback:

  Once you are scrolled back, Ctrl+R searches the CONTENT on
  screen instead of your command history - same key, same
  incremental feel, a different target:

    (search: fra_)   as you type, the newest matching line jumps
                      into view and is shown INVERTED, AND its
                      full text lands on your prompt - same as
                      history search already does with a matched
                      command, just now true for content search
                      too

    Ctrl+R (again)   step to the next OLDER match
    Backspace        shorten the fragment (search widens back)
    Return, Tab, or any other ordinary key
                      stop typing AND return you to your live
                      prompt, with the found line sitting there
                      ready to edit or run - the search is over,
                      same as it would be if you had just scrolled
                      back up yourself and typed it in by hand
    Esc              cancel - the found text is dropped, whatever
                      was on your prompt before Ctrl+R comes back

  n and N step through the SAME fragment's older/newer matches
  whenever you are scrolled back for any other reason (plain
  Shift/Ctrl+Up, the wheel) after a search - handy for re-checking
  a match without retyping it, but Return/Tab/typing no longer
  leave you parked at one on their own; they always hand the live
  prompt straight back.

  This works in raw mode too, on a raw client that is NOT on the
  alternate screen (CRAW:, or More/Ed's own restored transcript
  once you have quit them) - the same "no scrollback on the
  alternate screen" rule above applies here too, since there is
  nothing on screen to search until it does. Whatever you find
  stays put until you scroll, search again, or return to live.


11. COPY AND PASTE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Selecting:

    drag                  select a range; output FREEZES while you
                          hold the button, exactly like the stock
                          console, and resumes on release
    double-click          select the word under the pointer
    triple-click          select the whole line

  Releasing a drag - or the click selections immediately - copies
  the text to clipboard.device unit 0 as IFF FTXT, the format the
  stock console family uses. So:

    - copy in CCON:, paste in a stock CON: window: works
    - copy in stock CON:, paste in CCON:: works

  Pasting:

    RAMIGA-V   paste the clipboard as typed input. In raw mode the
               program receives the bytes as they are (pasting into
               Ed works), up to about 2000 bytes in one go - past
               that the tail is dropped and the window beeps, so
               paste a long file in pieces. In COOKED mode, only
               the FIRST line lands live - looking exactly like
               anything you typed, no markers, no symbols. There
               is no size cap in cooked mode; the rest queues.
               If the clip has more lines, a grey hint appears
               below the prompt: "N more lines
               queued - Enter runs this one, Esc cancels all." Each
               Enter runs the line on screen and loads the next;
               nothing later in the paste ever runs on its own, and
               Esc at any point drops the whole rest of the queue,
               not just the visible line.
    RAMIGA+SHIFT+V
               paste the OLD way for just this once: every line in
               the clip runs immediately as it lands, LF for Return.
    RAMIGA-C   re-copy the standing highlight.

  PASTEEXEC (an open option, section 5) makes a window behave like
  RAMIGA+SHIFT+V for EVERY paste, if you want the old behaviour as
  the default rather than the exception.

  Selection works on the scrollback view as well - scroll back,
  copy an old error, snap live, paste it.

  You can select the line you are still typing; the prompt and the
  edit line are ordinary cells to the selection machinery.


12. RAW MODE AND CRAW:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Programs switch a CCON: stream between cooked and raw with the
  usual SetMode/ACTION_SCREEN_MODE - fullscreen programs do this
  themselves. In raw mode every key becomes bytes for the program
  (arrows and F-keys as CSI sequences, Ctrl+C as a plain byte 3),
  and the console shows the classic block cursor.

  CRAW: is the same handler mounted a second time with a startup
  argument that opens every stream raw from the first byte - the
  RAW: counterpart:

    type somefile >CRAW:0/0/500/150/t/WAIT

  Both devices can be mounted and used at the same time; each runs
  as its own handler process.


13. RUNNING FULLSCREEN PROGRAMS (ED, MORE)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Ed and More work as they do on stock CON:, including the parts
  that usually break on replacement consoles:

    - Ed's MENUS drop and pick. Menu picks travel the same route
      they take over stock CON: (as input events, not IDCMP), which
      is the route Ed is actually written against.
    - Ed re-measures itself when you resize the window.
    - More's single-key paging uses real timed WAIT_CHARs.
    - The block cursor is drawn by the console, as Ed expects.
    - Swedish (and other) dead-key composition works in raw mode.
    - Ed's own line-by-line document scrolling (moving the cursor
      past the top or bottom of the visible window) uses the
      standard ANSI Scroll Up/Down controls, and CCON: honours
      them properly - the WHOLE view shifts, not just the one new
      line.
    - More restores your scrollback transcript exactly as it found
      it on exit: it brackets its session in CSI ?47h / ?47l, the
      same alternate-screen sequence xterm honours, and CCON:
      answers it the same way xterm does - pages you viewed in More
      do not enter your history, and quitting snaps back to your
      prompt instantly, pixel for pixel. Any client that sends the
      same sequence gets the same treatment.
    - Ed quits from its close gadget: the click is reported to Ed
      the way V47 defines it (Ed requests close-gadget reports at
      startup, alongside its menus and resize), so Ed runs its own
      quit flow instead of being cut off mid-session.
    - Quitting Ed leaves no stray empty line: Ed ends its session
      with a tidy newline meant for consoles that cannot restore
      the screen behind it; CCON: restores your transcript exactly,
      so that one redundant newline is dropped and the new prompt
      lands directly under your command. (Stock V47 shows the blank
      line; this is CCON: being deliberately nicer.)
    - Resizing the window WHILE Ed runs is safe: the fullscreen
      page is never re-wrapped into your scrollback, the window
      border stays drawn, Ed re-measures and repaints at the new
      size - and if you then quit, your transcript comes back
      re-wrapped to the new width (stock, and earlier CCON:,
      simply lost it).

  And unlike stock CON:, Ctrl+Up/Down and the wheel still scroll
  the view while these programs run - except on the alternate
  screen (More mid-page), where scrolling is refused, xterm manners.


14. ICONIFY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Press RIGHT-AMIGA + I in any CCON: window and it vanishes to an
  icon on the Workbench. Double-click the icon and the window comes
  straight back, exactly as you left it - the same scrollback, a
  half-typed command line, the cursor and colours all intact, at the
  size and position it had when it went away (so a window you had
  resized or dragged returns where you left it, not where it first
  opened).

  The console keeps running while iconified: a program still printing
  simply pauses (its next write waits) until you restore the window,
  then its output flushes and carries on. A program waiting for input
  just waits, as it would anyway.

  It works from a shell prompt and from a fullscreen program like Ed
  alike - the shortcut is caught before the client ever sees the key.

  The icon is built into the handler - nothing extra to install. Each
  iconified window gets its own "CCON" icon on the Workbench.


15. REPLACING THE SYSTEM CONSOLE (EXPERIMENTAL)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  CCON:'s own mountlist also carries CON: and RAW: stanzas,
  pointing at the exact same handler - the trick KingCON uses to
  become the system console. Dismount the stock devices, then
  mount CCON: under their names instead:

    Assign CON: DISMOUNT
    Assign RAW: DISMOUNT
    Mount CON: FROM DEVS:CCON-mountlist
    Mount RAW: FROM DEVS:CCON-mountlist

  From that point on, EVERY console the system opens - Startup-
  Sequence output, requesters, EndCLI, a plain NewShell CON: -
  opens through CCON: instead. A window already open when you run
  the Assign/Mount pair keeps whatever handler it already had;
  only NEW opens are affected.

  This needs no code changes to work: the shell's console probe
  (section 2) never checks which device name it was opened under,
  only what CCON: answers - so it hands editing to itself under
  CON: exactly as it does under its own name. Boot-tested working,
  including being made permanent via S:User-Startup (below).

  Two cosmetic-only quirks, not bugs: a window opened this way
  still shows "CCON:" as its default title, and it still answers
  "CCON" (not "CON ") to low-level tools that ask a handler's name
  - neither affects how it behaves.

  Put the Assign/Mount lines in S:User-Startup, NOT in Startup-
  Sequence itself, so anything Startup-Sequence needs CON: for
  before that point still gets the stock console - only your own
  session onward runs on CCON:.

  Marked experimental because the blast radius is different from
  everything else in this handbook: instead of "windows you asked
  for," it becomes "every console the OS opens." To undo it for
  the rest of a session, Assign CON:/RAW: DISMOUNT again and
  re-Mount the stock devices from DEVS:mountlist; a reboot undoes
  it for good if you have not made it permanent yet.


16. HOW IT WORKS, BRIEFLY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  CCON: is a DOS packet handler written in Amiga E. A few of its
  load-bearing choices:

  Keys arrive the way console.device's own do: an input.device
  handler sits just below Intuition in the input chain, takes
  events for the active CCON: window, and runs them through
  keymap.library. If the chain cannot be installed, the handler
  falls back to window (IDCMP) input automatically.

  The 3.2 shell probes each console at startup and, if it likes
  the answer, runs its OWN line editor. CCON: answers the probe so
  the shell leaves editing to the console - which is what makes
  history, ghosts, completion and search possible at the prompt.

  Colour lives in two worlds that must not mix. With WBPENS the
  palette is declared truly ANSI: pen conventions apply as-is and
  bold maps to the bright pens. On any other screen, plain SGR
  30-37 stay raw pen numbers (what Workbench-pen programs like Ed
  mean), while the bold forms - ANSI colour intent, the ls scheme -
  are translated BY COLOUR to the screen's nearest real pens. So
  directories are genuinely blue everywhere, and Ed is never red.

  Each window's display is backed by a scrollback model (512
  lines by default, LINES=n for more up to 5000) with one
  attribute byte per cell
  plus a style byte for SGR 3/4/7 (italic, underline, inverse -
  inverse is a pen swap at paint time, never a stored colour).
  Redraws, scrollback, selection repaints, menu restores and the
  Ctrl+R prompt restore all read from it.

  Output is rendered model-first (1.2.2): a write's bytes land in
  the scrollback model, and the screen catches up with at most ONE
  scroll blit per write - or none at all, when a whole screenful
  (or a form feed) went past and the grid is simply rebuilt from
  the model. The write itself is answered as soon as its bytes are
  safely copied; the pixels follow within a frame (20 ms), and
  bursts of output pool so that many lines share one blit - which
  is why a long listing no longer runs at the blitter's pace.
  Anything that must see settled output settles it first, in
  order: reads (More's cursor-position handshake included), mode
  switches, keystrokes, selection, paste, resizing, iconify and
  closing. Output still freezes while you drag a selection, as
  stock does. Writes larger than 4K, and consoles mounted without
  a scrollback model, take the fully synchronous path.

  Rendering is also plane-masked (1.2.3): CCON tracks which pens
  the transcript has drawn with and masks its drawing and its
  scroll blits down to the bitplanes those pens can occupy - plain
  pen-1 text on a 16-colour screen moves one plane in four. This
  is the same trick the 3.2 console.device uses. The mask widens
  the instant a new colour appears (colour output always renders
  at full depth, correctly) and narrows again at a form feed, a
  resize, leaving a fullscreen program, or an iconify restore.
  Non-planar (RTG-style) screens are never masked.

  And a blank screen is never scrolled (1.2.4): when the visible
  area holds nothing, a scroll would move blank pixels to blank
  pixels, so CCON does not ask the blitter to do it at all. This
  is what stock CON: has always done, and on real hardware it is
  the difference between a bare-newline flood being the slowest
  thing the console does and one of the fastest. In the same
  release the full-screen editing sequences (insert and delete
  line and character, erase-to-end, scroll-region) stopped forcing
  an immediate redraw each - they update the model and repaint
  with the rest of the write's output in one batch, so Ed
  scrolling a document is far lighter, and a program waiting on a
  keystroke has its output drawn at once rather than on the batch
  timer, keeping editing immediate.

  A window with no FONT option opens in whatever font Font Prefs
  has set as "System Default Text" - the same font stock CON:
  honours - falling back to topaz 8 only if that font is missing
  or proportional.

  A program that sets its own window title (the xterm-style OSC
  sequence, ESC ] 0 ; title BEL) is remembered as the window's
  title from then on; leaving scrollback restores THAT title, not
  CCON:'s own.

  The window closes with its last handle; WAIT windows linger for
  their gadget. Every open parses its own name, so all options
  apply per window.


17. KNOWN LIMITATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  - The scrollback model costs about 120K per window at 80 columns
    and the default 512 lines (LINESn scales this up to 5000,
    or down to a floor of 100).
  - A window is at most 255 text columns wide. On a very wide
    screen in a small font the columns past 255 are unused.
  - Growing a window taller than its own LINESn ring leaves the
    extra rows blank: the ring cannot show more lines at once
    than it holds. Open the window with a larger LINESn if you
    mean to grow it a lot.
  - Pasting into a raw fullscreen program (Ed) is capped at about
    2000 bytes per paste; the window beeps if the rest was
    dropped. Cooked-mode pasting has no such limit - it queues
    line by line (section 11).
  - CSI K under a coloured background erases to black.
  - Completion: no quoted words, one menu page, no volume-name
    completion for a bare word.
  - SMART/SIMPLE and ALT are not implemented.
  - A borrowed window (WINDOW0xADDR) keeps its owner's font; FONT
    only applies to windows CCON: opens itself.
  - On 32+ colour and RTG screens, ls-style ANSI colours fall back
    to the default pen: the scrollback model stores one 16-pen
    nibble per cell, and deep-screen best-match pens land above
    that. (The autosuggestion ghost and the completion menu ARE
    coloured on such screens as of 1.2.5 - they live outside the
    model.) Lifting the cap for text colours means widening the
    model - planned, 1.3-scale.
  - Resizing while a fullscreen program is showing a page is safe
    (see section 13), but a program that does not watch for resize
    reports - More does not; Ed does - will not know to repaint:
    the window shows your transcript until its next repaint (in
    More, any paging key).
  - Tab completion and the history file talk to the filesystem
    with no timeout, so a wedged or still-spinning-up disk can
    block the window until that filesystem answers.


18. BUILDING FROM SOURCE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  The prebuilt binary is included; nothing needs compiling. To
  build it yourself, with the E-VO E compiler:

    evo ccon-handler.e LARGE

  The LARGE model is required as of 1.0. The source is one file,
  ccon-handler.e, and carries its design history as comments -
  including how an E binary survives being started as a handler,
  verified by disassembling the compiler's generated startup code.


19. FILES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  L/ccon-handler         the handler
  DEVS/CCON-mountlist    Mount CCON:, CRAW:, CON: or RAW: FROM
                         this - one file, four device stanzas
                         (the last two experimental, section 15),
                         same shape KingCON's own mountlist uses
  ccon.readme            short-form readme
  ccon.doc               this manual

